I checked your logic — the main issue is this line inside `showPage()`:

```js
cards[i].style.display = "block";
```

Your cards are inside a **flex container**:

```html
<div id="cardContainer" class="d-flex ...">
```

And each card is styled using flex:

```css
#cardContainer .card {
  flex: 0 0 25%;
  max-width: 25%;
  display: flex;
}
```

When you change the card to `display: block`, you **break the flex layout**, so Bootstrap/flex behavior stops working correctly — which is why pagination looks like it’s not changing.

---

# ✅ ✅ Fix (Very Important)

Change this line:

```js
cards[i].style.display = "block";
```

To this:

```js
cards[i].style.display = "flex";
```

So your corrected `showPage()` function becomes:

```js
function showPage(page) {
  cards.forEach((card) => {
    card.style.display = "none";
  });

  const start = (page - 1) * cardsPerPage;
  const end = start + cardsPerPage;

  for (let i = start; i < end && i < cards.length; i++) {
    cards[i].style.display = "flex"; // ✅ FIXED
  }

  prevBtn.parentElement.classList.toggle("disabled", page === 1);
  nextBtn.parentElement.classList.toggle("disabled", page === totalPages);
}
```

---

# 🔎 Why This Fix Works

Your cards were originally:

```css
display: flex;
```

But JavaScript was changing them to:

```css
display: block;
```

That breaks:

* `flex: 0 0 25%`
* equal width layout
* row alignment

So the layout appears frozen.

---

# 🚀 Even Better (Cleaner Solution)

Instead of hardcoding `"flex"`, you can restore default display like this:

```js
cards[i].style.display = "";
```

That way it uses whatever CSS already defines (cleaner approach).

---

# 🧠 Extra Improvement (Optional)

If you want smoother UX, you could add:

```js
#cardContainer .card {
  transition: opacity 0.3s ease;
}
```

And animate instead of hiding instantly.

